{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:66","names":{"en":"Sultans of Harar","tr":"Harar Sultanları","ar":"Salāṭīn Harar"},"country":["ET","ML"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1506,"extinct":1887},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"66","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sultans of Harar","parent_tribe":"1. Ahmed Gran kolu (Valaşma'); 2. Ali b. Dâvûd kolu","ethnic_origin":"Somali / Arap / Etiyopyalı Müslüman","capital":"Harar; Ausa (bazı 1. kol sultanları)","region_primary":"Harar (Güneydoğu Etiyopya)","regions_all":"Harar; Ausa (1. kol geç dönem)","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":"Valaşma' İfat Sultanlığı","successor":"Etiyopya İmparatoru Menelik'in fethi (1304/1887)","government_type":"Sultanlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Sultans of Harar governed the Horn of Africa's most important Islamic cultural center for four centuries. Playing a key role in spreading Islam among Somali and Galla peoples, this sultanate established regional legitimacy through its own coinage system.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"9.31","capital_lon":"42.12","century_start":16,"century_end":19}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:64","names":{"en":"Mazrū'ī Liwali","tr":"Mombasa Mezrûî Valileri","ar":"al-Mazrū'iyyūn fī Manbasa"},"country":["ET","ML","NE","NG","SD","SO"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":1837},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"64","atlas_name_en_original":"The Mazrū'ī Liwalis or Governors of Mombasa","parent_tribe":"Mezrûî ailesi (Umân kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Umânlı)","capital":"Mombasa","region_primary":"Mombasa ve Pemba adası (Doğu Afrika kıyısı)","regions_all":"Mombasa; Pemba adası","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":"Portekiz yönetimi","successor":"Bû Saîdî doğrudan kontrolü (Sa'îd b. Sultān)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Mazrū'ī governors ruled Mombasa for approximately 140 years after the end of Portuguese control. Operating semi-independently from Bū Sa'īdī sultans, they competed for control of East African coastal trade.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"-4.05","capital_lon":"39.67","century_start":17,"century_end":19}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:63","names":{"en":"Nabhānī","tr":"Pate Nâbhânî Hükümdarları","ar":"Āl al-Nabhānī fī Bātā"},"country":["ET","ML","NE","NG","SD","SO"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1203,"extinct":1894},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"63","atlas_name_en_original":"The Nabhānī Rulers of Pate","parent_tribe":"Nâbhânî kabile grubu (Umân kökenli)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Umânlı) / Svahili","capital":"Pate","region_primary":"Pate adası (Kenya kıyısı, Lamu takımadası)","regions_all":"Pate; Vitu (kara tarafı); Lamu takımadası","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":null,"successor":"İngiliz sömürge yönetimi (1312/1894)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Nabhānī rulers of Pate governed for seven centuries on Kenya's Lamu archipelago, representing the African node of Indian Ocean trade networks. This Omani Arab dynasty integrated with Swahili culture to build a distinctive coastal Islamic civilization.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"-2.08","capital_lon":"41.05","century_start":13,"century_end":19}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:62","names":{"en":"Sultans of Kilwa","tr":"Kilva Sultanları","ar":"Salāṭīn Kilwa"},"country":["ET","ML","NE","NG","SD","SO"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":null,"extinct":null},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"62","atlas_name_en_original":"The Sultans of Kilwa","parent_tribe":"1. Şîrâzî hanedanı; 2. Mehdâlî Seyyidler","ethnic_origin":"Arap/Şîrâzî (iddia) / Svahili","capital":"Kilva (Quiloa)","region_primary":"Kilva adası (Tanzanya kıyısı)","regions_all":"Kilva (Kilwa Kisawani); Doğu Afrika kıyı ticareti","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":null,"successor":"Portekiz vasalları; ardından Umânlı kontrol; Bû Saîdîler (Zengibar)","government_type":"Sultanlık","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Kilwa Sultans were a Swahili dynasty controlling gold, ivory, and slave trade as the center of international maritime commerce on the East African coast. While the Shirazi origin claim is debated, Kilwa's minted coins evidence East Africa's earliest monetary system.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"-8.96","capital_lon":"39.52","century_start":null,"century_end":null}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:65","names":{"en":"Āl Bū Sa'īd in East Africa","tr":"Doğu Afrika Âl Bû Saîdîleri (Zengibar)","ar":"Āl Bū Sa'īd fī Sharq Ifrīqiyā"},"country":["ET","ML","NE","NG","SD","SO"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1840,"extinct":1964},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"65","atlas_name_en_original":"The Āl Bū Sa'īd in East Africa","parent_tribe":"Âl Bû Saîd ailesi (Umân)","ethnic_origin":"Arap (Umânlı)","capital":"Zengibar","region_primary":"Zengibar ve Doğu Afrika kıyısı","regions_all":"Zengibar; Pemba; Kilva; Mogadişu'dan Cape Delgado'ya kadar","geographic_zone":"Doğu/Batı Afrika","predecessor":"Mezrûîler (Mombasa); Ya'rubîler (genel Doğu Afrika)","successor":"Zengibar Cumhuriyeti → Tanzanya Birleşik Cumhuriyeti (1964)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Bū Sa'īdī of Zanzibar moved their sultanate's capital from Oman to East Africa, building an island empire based on the clove trade. Entering international diplomacy through Western consulates, the state gradually lost independence under British protectorate.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"-6.16","capital_lon":"39.19","century_start":19,"century_end":20}}
